Presently, we have confirmed that V4L2 works correctly with the R200 camera when using Linux 4.2.3.

See http://www.yourownlinux.com/2015/10/how-to-install-linux-kernel-4-2-3-in-linux.html for information on how to install Linux 4.2.3 in Ubuntu.

We then needed to apply our kernel patches. We checked out the 4.2.3 sources and applied the three patches as described in the SOURCES file here:

http://kernel.ubuntu.com/~kernel-ppa/mainline/v4.2.3-unstable/

After that we mostly followed the instructions from the RealSense ROS patch:

KBASE=`pwd`

patch -p1 < $DIR/../patches/linux-lts-saucy-3_11_0.patch

cp /boot/config-`uname -r` .config
cp  /usr/src/linux-headers-`uname -r`/Module.symvers .
make scripts oldconfig modules_prepare
cd drivers/media/usb/uvc
make -C $KBASE M=$KBASE/drivers/media/usb/uvc/ modules

## Copy module
sudo cp $KBASE/drivers/media/usb/uvc/uvcvideo.ko /lib/modules/`uname -r`/kernel/drivers/media/usb/uvc/uvcvideo.ko
## Remove old module if it's inserted
sudo rmmod uvcvideo.ko